@blackrobe2007 The third row in the matrix says that 0 = b3 - b2 - b1, so the values for b1, b2 and b3 must satisfy the result 0.
And the numbers 1, 5 and 6 for b1, b2 and b3 are good because they turn the equation 0 = b3 - b2 - b1 into 0 = 6 - 5 - 1, which is true.

There is an infinite number of other possible solutions as well --- for example, you could choose b1, b2 and b3 to be 50, 100 and 150, and in that case you would get 0 = 150 - 100 - 50, which is also true. 9Q1q7s1jTzU "8. Solving Ax = b: Row Reduced Form R" "MIT 18.06 Linear Algebra

